{
  "The SVD of a matrix A is A = USV^T. What are the properties of U and V?": "",
  "U and V are both diagonal": "",
  "U and V are both upper triangular": "",
  "U and V are both orthogonal (unitary) matrices": "",
  "U is orthogonal but V is not": "",
  "In the SVD A = USV^T, U (m x m) and V (n x n) are orthogonal matrices. S (m x n) is a diagonal matrix of singular values. For complex matrices, U and V are unitary.": "",
  "The singular values of a matrix A are the square roots of the eigenvalues of which matrix?": "",
  "A + A^T, particularly": "",
  "A^T A (or equivalently A A^T)": "",
  "A^(-1), particularly": "",
  "A itself, particularly": "",
  "The singular values sigma_i = sqrt(lambda_i(A^T A)). Since A^T A is positive semi-definite, its eigenvalues are non-negative, making the square roots real and non-negative.": "",
  "If A is a 3x2 matrix with rank 2, how many nonzero singular values does A have?": "",
  "3": "",
  "5": "",
  "1": "",
  "2": "",
  "The number of nonzero singular values equals the rank of the matrix. Since rank(A) = 2, there are exactly 2 nonzero singular values.": "",
  "What is the relationship between the singular values and the 2-norm (operator norm) of a matrix?": "",
  "||A||_2 = sigma_1 (the largest singular value)": "",
  "||A||_2 = product of all singular values": "",
  "||A||_2 = sum of all singular values": "",
  "||A||_2 = sigma_n (the smallest singular value)": "",
  "The operator 2-norm (spectral norm) of a matrix equals its largest singular value: ||A||_2 = sigma_1 = max(||Ax|| / ||x||). This represents the maximum stretching factor of A.": "",
  "The condition number of a matrix A (in the 2-norm) is defined as:": "",
  "sigma_1 / sigma_r (largest / smallest nonzero singular value)": "",
  "det(A), particularly regarding small as observed": "",
  "sigma_1 + sigma_r, particularly regarding large": "",
  "sigma_1 * sigma_r, particularly regarding kappa": "",
  "The condition number kappa(A) = sigma_1 / sigma_r measures sensitivity to perturbations. A large condition number means the matrix is ill-conditioned and small changes in input cause large changes in output.": "",
  "The columns of V in A = USV^T are called the right singular vectors. They are the eigenvectors of which matrix?": "",
  "A^T A": "",
  "A": "",
  "A A^T": "",
  "S": "",
  "From A = USV^T, we get A^T A = VS^TSV^T = V(S^TS)V^T. So V diagonalizes A^T A, making V's columns the eigenvectors of A^T A.": "",
  "If a matrix A has singular values 5, 3, and 1, what is the Frobenius norm ||A||_F?": "",
  "5, par": "",
  "sqrt(35)": "",
  "9, par": "",
  "15, pa": "",
  "||A||_F = sqrt(sum of sigma_i^2) = sqrt(25 + 9 + 1) = sqrt(35). The Frobenius norm equals the square root of the sum of squared singular values.": "",
  "The best rank-k approximation of A (in Frobenius norm) is obtained by keeping only the top k singular values and setting the rest to zero. This result is known as:": "",
  "The spectral theorem": "",
  "The rank-nullity theorem": "",
  "The Cayley-Hamilton theorem": "",
  "The Eckart-Young-Mirsky theorem": "",
  "The Eckart-Young-Mirsky theorem states that the best rank-k approximation of A (minimizing ||A - B||_F over all rank-k matrices B) is the truncated SVD keeping the top k singular values.": "",
  "For a square invertible matrix A with singular values sigma_1 >= ... >= sigma_n > 0, the determinant |det(A)| equals:": "",
  "sigma_1 / sigma_n": "",
  "sigma_1 * sigma_2 * ... * sigma_n (product of all singular values)": "",
  "sigma_1 + sigma_2 + ... + sigma_n": "",
  "sigma_1 (the largest singular value)": "",
  "|det(A)| = |det(U)| * det(S) * |det(V^T)| = 1 * (sigma_1 * ... * sigma_n) * 1. The absolute value of the determinant equals the product of all singular values.": "",
  "Every matrix (including non-square matrices) has an SVD. True or false?": "",
  "False -- only invertible matrices have SVD": "",
  "True": "",
  "False -- only square matrices have SVD": "",
  "False -- only symmetric matrices have SVD": "",
  "Unlike eigendecomposition (which requires square matrices and may not exist for defective matrices), the SVD exists for every matrix of any size, including rectangular, singular, and non-square matrices.": "",
  "What is a 'singular value' of a matrix?": "",
  "A value that makes the matrix singular, particularly regarding values as typically measured in practice": "",
  "An eigenvalue of A that equals zero, particularly regarding values under normal circumstances": "",
  "A non-negative number equal to the square root of an eigenvalue of A^T A, representing how much A stretches in a particular direction": "",
  "The determinant of A, particularly regarding directions as typically measured in practice": "",
  "Singular values are the non-negative square roots of the eigenvalues of A^T A. They measure the amount of stretching that A applies along each of its principal directions (right singular vectors).": "",
  "What is the 'pseudoinverse' (Moore-Penrose inverse) A^+ of a matrix?": "",
  "A^+ = V S^+ U^T, where S^+ is obtained by inverting each nonzero singular value in S": "",
  "A^+ = (A^T A)^(-1), particularly regarding computed in accordance": "",
  "A^+ = A^T always, particularly regarding with when applying": "",
  "A^+ = A^(-1) for all matrices as determined by standard methodology": "",
  "The pseudoinverse is computed via SVD: replace each nonzero sigma_i with 1/sigma_i in S, then A^+ = V S^+ U^T. It gives the minimum-norm least-squares solution for any linear system.": "",
  "What is the 'truncated SVD'?": "",
  "The SVD with all singular values rounded to integers": "",
  "An approximation of A using only the top k singular values and their corresponding singular vectors": "",
  "Removing the U matrix from the decomposition": "",
  "The SVD computed on a smaller submatrix of A": "",
  "The truncated (or thin) SVD keeps only the k largest singular values and their corresponding left and right singular vectors: A_k = U_k S_k V_k^T. This is the optimal rank-k approximation.": "",
  "What does the 'condition number' of a matrix tell you?": "",
  "The number of iterations needed for convergence": "",
  "The rank of the matrix": "",
  "How sensitive the solution of Ax = b is to perturbations in A or b": "",
  "The number of nonzero entries in the matrix": "",
  "The condition number kappa(A) = sigma_max / sigma_min measures numerical sensitivity. A condition number of 10^k means you may lose about k digits of accuracy when solving Ax = b numerically.": "",
  "What are 'left singular vectors'?": "",
  "The columns of V, particularly regarding": "",
  "The columns of U in A = USV^T, which are the eigenvectors of AA^T": "",
  "The rows of A, particularly regarding space in": "",
  "The diagonal entries of S in accordance with classical theory": "",
  "Left singular vectors are the columns of U. They are eigenvectors of AA^T and form an orthonormal basis for the column space (and its complement) of A.": "",
  "What is the 'compact SVD' (also called thin SVD)?": "",
  "The SVD where U and V are compressed using another algorithm": "",
  "A = U_r S_r V_r^T where only the r nonzero singular values and corresponding vectors are kept (r = rank)": "",
  "A variant of SVD that only computes singular values": "",
  "The SVD of a small matrix": "",
  "The compact SVD uses only the r columns of U and V corresponding to nonzero singular values. For an m x n matrix of rank r, U_r is m x r, S_r is r x r, and V_r is n x r.": "",
  "What does 'low-rank approximation' mean in the SVD context?": "",
  "Reducing the number of rows in a matrix": "",
  "Finding a matrix with a small determinant": "",
  "Computing the smallest eigenvalue": "",
  "Approximating a matrix by one with fewer nonzero singular values, reducing its effective rank": "",
  "Low-rank approximation replaces a matrix with a nearby matrix of lower rank by zeroing out the smallest singular values. This is fundamental to data compression, noise reduction, and dimensionality reduction.": "",
  "What is the 'nuclear norm' (trace norm) of a matrix?": "",
  "The largest singular value": "",
  "The product of all singular values": "",
  "The sum of all singular values: ||A||_* = sigma_1 + sigma_2 + ... + sigma_r": "",
  "The sum of squared singular values": "",
  "The nuclear norm is the sum of singular values. It is the tightest convex relaxation of the rank function and is used in matrix completion and low-rank optimization problems.": "",
  "What is the geometric interpretation of the SVD?": "",
  "Every matrix is symmetric, particularly regarding axes when evaluated systematically": "",
  "Every matrix is a product of two rotations following conventional understanding": "",
  "Every linear transformation can be decomposed into a rotation (V^T), a scaling along axes (S), and another rotation (U)": "",
  "Every matrix maps circles to circles within the typical range of values": "",
  "The SVD decomposes any linear transformation into three steps: rotate/reflect input (V^T), scale along the coordinate axes (S), then rotate/reflect output (U). A unit sphere maps to an ellipsoid whose semi-axes are the singular values.": "",
  "What is 'randomized SVD'?": "",
  "An approximate SVD algorithm that uses random projections to efficiently compute the top singular values for very large matrices": "",
  "An SVD where U and V have random entries as predicted by standard models": "",
  "Generating random singular values for testing as predicted by standard models": "",
  "An SVD computed on a random subset of rows as predicted by standard models": "",
  "Randomized SVD uses random projections to find an approximate low-rank basis, then computes the SVD on the smaller projected matrix. It is much faster than full SVD for large matrices where only the top k singular values are needed.": "",
  "A data scientist compresses a 1000x800 image matrix using rank-20 SVD approximation. How many values must be stored for the compressed representation?": "",
  "20,000": "",
  "800,000": "",
  "1,000": "",
  "36,020": "",
  "Store 20 left singular vectors (1000 entries each = 20,000) + 20 right singular vectors (800 entries each = 16,000) + 20 singular values = 36,020. Compare to 800,000 for the full matrix -- about 22:1 compression.": "",
  "A machine learning engineer uses SVD for collaborative filtering. If the rating matrix is 10000x5000 with rank 3 (approximately), what are the dimensions of the compact SVD matrices U_3, S_3, V_3?": "",
